Isabel Metzger Machine Learning HW 2 PART B

B. Linear regression Choose your favorite biomedical dataset and perform linear regression to predict a
variable of interest. Briefly describe your data. Think and answer the following questions: • Use simple linear regression. How well does your model perform? How did you choose
the predictor variable?

• Use multiple linear regression. Do all the predictor variables you use contribute to the
prediction? How well does the model fit the data? Is it better than if you had a simple
linear regression model for every individual variable?

The data

This Data is the Pima Indians Diabetes set, which has 768 obs. of 9 variables.

pregnant: Number of times pregnant glucose: Plasma glucose concentration (glucose tolerance test) pressure: Diastolic blood pressure (mm Hg) triceps: Triceps skin fold thickness (mm) insulin: 2-Hour serum insulin (mu U/ml) mass: Body mass index (weight in kg/(height in meters squared) pedigree: Diabetes pedigree function age: Age (years) diabetes: Class variable (test for diabetes) This hw assignment will be on linear regression, trying to predict a numerical variable from another numerical variable.

?PimaIndiansDiabetes

For a pvalue less than 0.05 (such as the one in our case), the t-value should be above 1.96.

Although the fit does not look perfectly linear, there is indication that glucose and insulin are correlated. Building the linear model with the training data.

Another thing to note is the low R squared value. A typical “good R squared value” would be above 0.70. This model performs poorly with an R squared value of 0.1098.

Building the model

set.seed(42)
# using a 70 percent to 30 percent splot
train_faction <- 0.7
df <- PimaIndiansDiabetes
train_ind <- sample(nrow(df),round(train_faction*nrow(df)))
train_set <- df[train_ind,]
test_set <- df[-train_ind,]
lmMod <- lm(insulin ~ glucose, data=train_set)  # build the model
insPred <- predict(lmMod, test_set)  
summary(lmMod)

Below is another way to perform cross validation and ridge regression vs lasso regression, like that in our example during class.

library(broom)
library(glmnet)
y <- train_set$insulin
# selecting x to have what we have decided as the selected model above
x <- train_set %>% select(pregnant, glucose, pressure, triceps) %>% data.matrix()
lambdas =  10^seq(4, -2, by = -.1)  # chose 4 for the 4 predictive variables
cv_fit <- cv.glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0, lambda = lambdas)  # alpha set to 0 is for ridge regression
plot(cv_fit)

summary(cv_fit)
           Length Class  Mode     
lambda     61     -none- numeric  
cvm        61     -none- numeric  
cvsd       61     -none- numeric  
cvup       61     -none- numeric  
cvlo       61     -none- numeric  
nzero      61     -none- numeric  
name        1     -none- character
glmnet.fit 12     elnet  list     
lambda.min  1     -none- numeric  
lambda.1se  1     -none- numeric  
cv_fit$lambda.min
[1] 5.011872

The lambda min that showed the best fit for this type of model is 5.011872.

ridge.fit <- cv_fit$glmnet.fit
x_test <- test_set %>% select(pregnant, glucose, pressure, triceps) %>% data.matrix()
predictions_ridge <- predict(ridge.fit, s = 5.011872, x_test)
actuals_preds_ridgemodel <- data.frame(cbind(actuals=test_set$insulin, predictions_ridge)) 
correlation_accuracy_ridgemodel <- cor(actuals_preds_ridgemodel) 
names(actuals_preds_ridgemodel) <- c("Actuals", "PredictedValues")
actuals_preds_ridgemodel %>% ggplot(aes(Actuals, PredictedValues)) + geom_point() + ggtitle("Ridge Regression")

rsquared.ridgemodel <- 1 - sum((actuals_preds_ridgemodel$PredictedValues-actuals_preds_ridgemodel$Actuals)^2) / sum((actuals_preds_ridgemodel$Actuals-mean(actuals_preds_ridgemodel$Actuals))^2)
rsquared.ridgemodel
[1] 0.3665032

0.3665032 indicating that %36 percent of the variance is explained by this model.

Conclusion:

These models may not be the best fit for this data. However, we can see that although all show statistical significance. The first linear model, which only used glucose and insulin performed the worst. The second model, which included multiple variables, performed better, and lastly the ridge model had the highest Rsquared and performed the best out of the three.
